Social Science & Medicine

Volume 269, January 2021, 113572

Why public health framing matters: An experimental study of the effects of COVID-19 framing on prejudice and xenophobia in the United States

Author links open overlay panelLindsay Y.DhananiaBerkeleyFranzb
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.socscimed.2020.113572Get rights and content

Highlights

•

The framing of COVID-19 information shapes prejudice and xenophobia.

•

Emphasizing COVID-19's origin in China increases anti-Asian and xenophobic attitudes.

•

Emphasizing severe economic harm also increases negative outgroup attitudes.

•

Messaging about the health threat of the virus is unrelated to outgroup bias.

Abstract

The COVID-19 pandemic has triggered a notable increase in the expression of prejudicial and xenophobic attitudes that threaten the wellbeing of minority groups and contribute to the overall public health toll of the virus. However, while there is evidence documenting the growth in discrimination and xenophobia, little is known about how the COVID-19 outbreak is activating the expression of such negative attitudes. The goal of the current paper therefore was to investigate what aspects of the COVID-19 pandemic may be contributing to this rise in expressions of prejudice and xenophobia. More specifically, this study used an experimental design to assess the effects of using stigmatized language to describe the virus as well as the threat to physical health and economic wellbeing posed by the virus on COVID-19 prejudice. Data were collected from a national sample of 1451 adults residing within the United States. Results from 2 × 2 x 2 between-subjects analyses of covariance demonstrated that emphasizing the connection between China and COVID-19, rather than framing the virus neutrally, increased negative attitudes toward Asian Americans, beliefs that resources should be prioritized for Americans rather than immigrants, and general xenophobia. Emphasizing the severity of the economic impact of the virus also increased beliefs that Asian Americans are a threat to resources and general xenophobia. In contrast, messages which emphasized the serious health risks of COVID-19 did not increase bias toward Asian Americans or xenophobia. Our findings suggest that specific types of public health messaging related to infectious diseases, especially framing the virus in terms of its country of origin or its likely economic impact, may elicit prejudice and xenophobia. Public health campaigns that emphasize the severity of the virus, however, are not likely to trigger the same negative attitudes. Implications for public health responses to health crises are discussed.

1. Introduction

Over the last several months, countries across the world have observed a sharp increase in reports of tension, hostility, and violence targeting Asian people and other minority groups in response to the novel coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak. In the United States, reports of abuse against Asian Americans range from customers deserting Asian-owned restaurants and businesses (Chang, 2020), public verbal attacks against people of East Asian descent (Yoon-Ji Kang, 2020), Asian Americans being spit on or intentionally coughed on (Inskeep, 2020), and even physical assaults (Yang, 2020a). Recent evidence also points to the prevalence of such negative treatment, with nearly 40% of Asian Americans reporting that people have acted uncomfortable around them since the onset of the COVID-19 outbreak and over 30% reporting they had been the target of racial slurs or jokes (Ruiz et al., 2020).

Growing expressions of prejudice sparked by the outbreak has also not been limited to people of Asian descent and appears to have spilled over into general xenophobia. As examples, President Trump has used COVID-19 to justify efforts to limit or suspend immigration to the United States (The White House, 2020); Matteo Salvini, the leader of Italy's far-right political party, has used the virus to call for border closures after erroneously attempting to link the spread of the virus to African asylum seekers (Tondo, 2020); and reports indicate that African immigrants in China have been barred from restaurants and hotels because of fears that they are more likely to carry the virus (Yang, 2020b). More recently, the correspondence of new COVID-19 restrictions in the UK with the Islamic holiday, Eid-al-Adha, has added to existing stigma that racial/ethnic and religious minorities were already facing during the pandemic (Rahim, 2020).

The increases in discrimination and xenophobia following COVID-19 can have numerous detrimental effects for Asians and other minority groups that are being targeted during this time. One ramification that has already become obvious is the toll stigmatization has taken on the economic wellbeing of Asian Americans. Indeed, as just one example, unemployment rates in New York state have risen 6900% among Asian Americans, as compared to 1840% for White employees, at least in part because of widespread fear surrounding interacting with Asian employees or business owners (Liao, 2020). Asians and other minority groups have also reported increased fear and anxiety resulting from the spike in prejudice and discrimination (Ruiz et al., 2020), which can exacerbate the more general harmful effects of experiencing a public health crisis. The damage of stigmatization is also not constrained to short-term harm and the heightened stress that accompanies experiences of stigma can also pose threats to long-term physical and mental health (Pascoe and Richman, 2009).

The evidence of widespread prejudicial and xenophobic reactions to COVID-19 coupled with the substantial negative consequences makes clear the need to investigate how the COVID-19 outbreak may be increasing the expression of negative intergroup attitudes. To address this question, the current study utilizes an experimental design to examine three potential explanations for why COVID-19 may be activating expressions of prejudice toward people of Asian descent and broader xenophobic attitudes. Those explanations include the way messages about COVID-19 have been framed, the physical health threats posed by the virus, and the economic threat of the virus. In the sections below, we summarize each of these explanations and the corresponding evidence that supports their role in contributing to negative intergroup attitudes.

1.1. Message framing and COVID-19 prejudice: three potential explanations

There has been an abundance of research on attitudes towards immigrants and reviews of this literature demonstrate that, although there is some evidence that attitudes have become more favorable over time, natives continue to hold persistent negative views of immigrants (Ceobanu and Escandell, 2010; Citrin et al., 1997; Fussell, 2014). Negative attitudes toward immigrants and racial/ethnic outgroups also fluctuate across time and appear to be most acute during times of hardship (Citrin et al., 1997, Krosch et al., 2017). We draw on the extant literature on attitudes toward immigrants and other outgroups to propose that, like previous times of adversity, the COVID-19 pandemic may be precipitating heightened expressions of prejudice and xenophobia. The current study also extends previous findings by examining the specific facets of the COVID-19 pandemic that may be contributing to heightened prejudice and xenophobia. In the paragraphs below, we explicate three potential explanations for the linkage between COVID-19 and the growing expressions of negative outgroup attitudes.

The first potential explanation for the observed increase in prejudice and xenophobia in response to COVID-19 is the use of stigmatizing language to describe the virus. The language public health officials, governmental leaders, and others have used to discuss COVID-19 has been the subject of much public discourse and deep disagreements have emerged regarding different framing techniques (Fischer, 2020). Whereas some leaders and officials have emphasized the need to discuss the virus using its scientific name and origin, others have consistently used language that emphasizes the linkage between the virus and its origin in China. The latter approach is illustrated by governmental leaders, news anchors, and members of the public referring to the virus as the “Chinese virus” (Chang, 2020), the “Wuhan virus” (Mangan, 2020), the “foreign virus” (Choi, 2020), the “kung flu” (Rogers et al., 2020), and other monikers that connect the virus to its country of origin. Outside of just naming, some discourse surrounding the virus has also centered on criticisms of Chinese cultural practices, sensationalized depictions of Chinese food outlets (Pavel and Engelke, 2020), and skepticism of the Chinese government (Feng and Cheng, 2020), all of which may increase the connection between the virus and people of Chinese descent. More recently, there have also been more explicit attempts to levy blame for the virus against China as President Trump and other U.S. political leaders have advocated for taking punitive action against China to hold them accountable for the outbreak (Kephart, 2020, Nakamura and Morello, 2020).

Framing the virus in this way has garnered considerable attention as some have been critical of this approach and warned that it may stoke fear of and racism toward people of East Asian descent (Chiu, 2020; Devakumar et al., 2020; Itkowitz, 2020), especially in the context of existing negative attitudes toward immigrants in the U.S. (Fussell, 2014). These criticisms also comport with theoretical and empirical work on the connection between disease and outgroup attitudes. One theoretical perspective asserts that the tendency to link outgroups with the threat of contracting a disease or illness is rooted in an adaptive and self-protective response (Faulkner et al., 2004). That is, contact with new populations is associated with an increased risk of exposure to contagious illnesses for which one has no acquired immunity (Navarrete and Fessler, 2006) which has been argued to motivate people to avoid unknown groups of people as a way to mitigate the risk of illness (Faulkner et al., 2004). Although it is difficult to determine whether this tendency is indeed rooted in the proposed motivational processes, ample empirical research confirms that people associate disease risk more strongly with outgroup rather than ingroup members (e.g., Faulkner et al., 2004; Huang et al., 2011; Navarrete and Fessler, 2006).

Framing techniques that emphasize the connection between the virus and people of Asian descent, or between the virus and foreigners more broadly, may therefore increase prejudicial responses by reinforcing existing patterns of interpreting risk relative to infectious diseases. These messages can appear to substantiate concerns that outgroups are at a higher risk for transmitting illnesses through priming a connection between those groups and the disease, placing blame on members of those groups for the outbreak, and linking specific cultural practices to the disease. This rationale also comports with previous studies which have found that media coverage of immigration and the ways the media frame immigrants can exacerbate anti-immigrant attitudes (Chavez, 2001, 2013; Hopkins, 2010). We therefore hypothesize that exposure to messages that emphasize the connection between COVID-19 and its origin in China will be associated with increased prejudice toward people of Asian descent as well as more xenophobic attitudes.

Beyond framing COVID-19 as originating in China, other portrayals of the virus may help explain rising expressions of racism and xenophobia observed in response to COVID-19. More specifically, COVID-19 has been accompanied by substantial threats to physical health and economic wellbeing and framing the virus in ways that emphasize these threats may also be activating prejudice (Riek et al., 2006). This assertion is congruent with two dominant theoretical perspectives on the causes of intergroup conflict. The first perspective is that of intergroup threat theories, which propose that intergroup tensions are triggered when an outgroup is perceived as a threat to an ingroup's goals, general well-being, or economic resources, or may otherwise inflict harm upon the ingroup (Sherif and Sherif, 1969). Intergroup threat theories further maintain that perceptions that an outgroup is a threat will then elicit outgroup bias as a means of preserving the wellbeing and interests of the ingroup (Stephan et al., 2009). Indeed, there is evidence that real or symbolic threats to individual socioeconomic status or the broader well-being of one's country are associated with anti-immigrant attitudes (Ceobanu and Escandell, 2010; Citrin et al., 1997; Fussell, 2014). Importantly, attitudes toward specific racial/ethnic groups seem to spillover to immigrants more broadly, suggesting that general ethnocentrism or xenophobia can be strengthened even in contexts where threats are associated only with specific racial outgroups (Ceobanu and Escandell, 2010; Kinder and Kam, 2010).

A second perspective comes from work on the effects of scarcity on intergroup bias. This perspective posits that resource scarcity drives intergroup conflict because it creates perceptions that outgroups are threatening one's access to limited resources and because discrimination allows people to justify withholding such limited resources from others (Rodenheffer et al., 2012, Skitka and Tetlock, 1992). Considerable empirical evidence supports both the intergroup threat perspective and the resource scarcity perspective. Indeed, perceived intergroup threat is associated with negative outgroup attitudes (Riek et al., 2006), including increased fear and resentment (Stephan et al., 2008) and greater avoidance, aggression, and retaliation (Stephan et al., 2009). As noted above, studies have also linked intergroup threat to negative attitudes toward immigrants more specifically (Ceobanu and Escandell, 2010; Citrin et al., 1997; Fussell, 2014). Further, resource scarcity increases outgroup categorizations (Rodenheffer et al., 2012), heightens perceptions of phenotypic characteristics that can be used to differentiate outgroup members from ingroup members (Krosch and Amodio, 2014), and results in discriminatory behaviors (Krosch et al., 2017).

In the context of COVID-19, these theories suggest that the observed increases in prejudice and xenophobia may therefore be explained by perceptions that one's physical health or economic wellbeing are threatened by the outbreak. This seems likely given the severity of the symptoms associated with COVID-19 as well as the relatively high reproduction and mortality rate of the virus (Peterson, 2020). Similarly, the economic damage associated with the virus has been substantial and has resulted in the loss of income, joblessness, and economic insecurity for many (Bureau of Labor Statistics, 2020, John Hopkins University, 2020). Moreover, prejudice and xenophobia may be heightened not only because of general threats to physical and economic wellbeing but also because these threats have become coupled with people of Asian descent or other groups perceived as outsiders. Based on this, we hypothesize that exposure to messages that describe severe rather than mild health and economic effects of the virus will be associated not only with greater prejudice toward Asians but also greater xenophobia.

1.2. The current study

The goal of this paper is to examine the effects of using stigmatized language to describe COVID-19 as well as the effects of portraying the severity of the physical health threat and economic threat of the virus on prejudicial and xenophobic attitudes to help explain the rising rates of harassment and discrimination in response to COVID-19. Building on previous work that links media framing to anti-immigrant attitudes (Fussell, 2014), we explore how different facets of the public health response to the COVID-19 pandemic may contribute to anti-Asian prejudice and xenophobia in the U.S. Further, unlike most existing studies, we utilize an experimental study design to ascertain the material impact of framing techniques on prejudice and xenophobia. Using this design, we are able to test which types of framing--messages that emphasize the virus's linkage to China, descriptions of the severity of the virus's threat to physical health, and descriptions of the severity of the virus's economic threat--shape bias toward people of Asian descent and broader xenophobia.

This study contributes to our understanding of public health responses to COVID-19 in three key ways. First, this study provides insight into the most effective ways to inform the public about COVID-19 and what types of framing may exacerbate harm for vulnerable groups. In doing so, the findings can provide guidance to public health officials, governmental leaders, and news outlets regarding the communication techniques they should adopt when disseminating COVID-19 information to the public. Relatedly, our findings also contribute to the ongoing public debate about the framing of public health responses to COVID-19 by determining whether criticisms of framing the virus in terms of its origin are substantiated. There is anecdotal evidence that seems to connect public health messaging that frames the virus as a “foreign” threat that originated in China to the recent growth in expressions of racism and xenophobia, but there have not yet been attempts to empirically examine this relationship, particularly using experimental methods that can demonstrate causality. We argue this an important empirical question because it can document the potential harmful effects of such messages for the health and well-being of racial/ethnic minority groups. Finally, this study has implications for future infectious disease outbreaks. It is predicted that another infectious disease outbreak is likely (Altizer et al., 2013) and, as we have seen with COVID-19, early communication about viruses is critical in shaping the public's attitudes and responses. It is thus important to use evidence-based communication strategies that have low risk for stigmatization, and the current findings can provide guidance for communicating about future public health threats.

2. Method

2.1. Participants

Data were collected from a national sample of 1580 adults residing within the United States. Participants were recruited to take part in a study on how information about the coronavirus can affect attitudes and beliefs. Data were collected online via a Qualtrics Panel, which is a participant recruitment service that uses online recruitment platforms to identify eligible participants. Data collection took place in May 2020. The sample size was determined by an a priori power analysis based on the type of analysis to be performed (i.e., ANCOVA), the number of covariates (i.e., 6), an alpha of .05, and an estimated effect size of 0.15. The a priori power analysis suggested a required sample size of at least 1192 participants. Of the 1580 participants who completed the survey, 129 were removed for speeding or failing a data quality check item. This resulted in a sample of 1451 participants who completed at least part of the survey. Of those participants, 1278 provided responses to the two measures assessing attitudes toward Asian Americans and 1258 provided responses to the two measures assessing xenophobic attitudes.

Approximately half of our participants identified their gender as male (50.4%), 49.5% were female, and 0.1% identified as nonbinary or thirdgender. The average age of our participants was 39.34 (SD = 13.86). The most commonly reported racial/ethnic identity was White/Caucasian (73.3%) followed by Black or African American (10.4%), Hispanic or Latinx (8.1%), Asian (6.9%), American Indian or Alaskan Native (2.4%), Native Hawaiian or Pacific Islander (0.4%), and Middle Eastern (0.3%). An additional 1% of our sample selected “other” for their racial/ethnic identity. The racial/ethnic composition of our sample is similar to the general composition of the United States with the exception that Hispanic/Latinx participants were underrepresented.

Our sample also varied according to their educational background, with 18.1% earning a high school diploma, 15.8% completing some college, 10.9% holding an associate's degree, 26.7% holding a bachelor's degree, 19.8% holding a master's degree, and 8.6% holding a doctoral or professional degree. Finally, 43.1% of our sample identified as democrats, 26.9% as independents, and 30.0% as republicans.

2.2. Procedures and measures

Participants were randomly assigned to read a passage about the coronavirus that differed in the framing of the origin of the virus, the described severity of the health threat of the virus, and the described severity of the economic impact of the virus. The origin of the virus was manipulated by presenting participants with a paragraph that either framed the virus in terms of its origin in China or was framed without connection to China. The Chinese framing condition emphasized that COVID-19 began in and spread outwardly from China and was linked to cultural practices (i.e., food markets) in China. The neutral condition instead emphasized that the virus originated from a mutation of existing viruses and made no reference to China. To manipulate the perceived health threat of the virus, participants were presented with a paragraph that either described the virus as a severe threat to physical health or a mild threat. These conditions differed in their descriptions of the long-term consequences of the virus, the expected duration of the outbreak, when a vaccine or treatment would be available, and information about immunity.

Finally, we manipulated economic threat by describing either a severe impact to the economy or a mild impact. The severe impact condition emphasized continued business closures, high unemployment, and slow economic recovery whereas the mild impact condition emphasized businesses that were already reopening, employees that were getting back to work, and predictions of quick economic recovery. This resulted in a 2 (neutral framing vs. Chinese framing) x 2 (low vs. high health threat) x 2 (low vs. high economic threat) between-subjects design.

After reading the informational passage about the virus, participants were then asked to respond to four measures of their attitudes and beliefs about Asian Americans and immigrants more generally (the items for each measure can be found in Appendix A). The response scale for all measures ranged from 1 (strongly disagree) to 5 (strongly agree).

The first measure contained four items which assessed COVID-19-specific beliefs about people of Asian descent. This measure was created for the current study and the items asked participants the extent to which they agree with the following statements: “It is understandable that people are afraid of Asian Americans because of the COVID-19 outbreak,” “The coronavirus outbreak shows the dangers of Asian cultural practices,” “Asian people are to blame for the coronavirus outbreak,” and “Asian Americans should be treated differently due to COVID-19.” This scale demonstrated adequate reliability” (α = 0.85).

The second measure examined perceptions that Asian Americans are a threat to the resources of others in the United States. This measure consisted of 11 items taken from the Attitudes toward Asian Americans Scale (Ho and Jackson, 2001). We selected items from the original scale that focused on perceptions that Asian Americans threaten resources in the U.S. Example items are, “Asian Americans are out to drain American resources,” and “Asian Americans make the job market too competitive.” The reliability for the shortened scale was α = 0.91.

We also assessed beliefs about prioritizing financial and healthcare resources for American citizens rather than immigrants in response to COVID-19. The self-created 7-item measure asked participants to rate the extent to which they agreed with statements such as, “If hospitals become overwhelmed, we should prioritize health care for American citizens over caring for immigrants,” and “Economic support to help those who are financially struggling because of the coronavirus outbreak should be prioritized for Americans rather than immigrants.” This scale also demonstrated adequate reliability (α = .88).

We finally measured general xenophobic attitudes that were not specific to COVID-19 responses. To do so, we used seven items from the 2016 American National Election Study to assess general beliefs about immigrants (American National Election Studies, 2016). Example items include, “America's culture is generally harmed by immigrants,” and “To be truly American, it is important to be born in the United States.” The reliability of the general xenophobia scale was α = 0.88.

2.3. Analyses

Study hypotheses were tested by estimating 2 × 2 × 2 between-subjects analysis of covariance (ANCOVA) models which examined the effects of framing, health threat, and economic threat on the four measures of outgroup attitudes. This analytical strategy was adopted because it allows us to assess the independent effects of each of the manipulated framing techniques (i.e., the described origin of the virus, the severity of the health threat of the virus, and the severity of the economic threat of the virus) as well as any potential interaction effects between or among the framing techniques. It is possible for interaction effects to emerge wherein exposure to a certain combination of framing techniques influences outgroup attitudes in unique ways. For example, exposure to a certain condition for one framing technique may amplify the effects of exposure to a certain condition for another framing technique. For this reason, we assess the full ANCOVA model which includes main effects and interaction effects.

Our analyses additionally controlled for several demographic variables that may be relevant to our dependent measures. Specifically, we controlled for gender, education, and political affiliation because prior findings suggest these demographic variables are associated with outgroup attitudes, including susceptibility to anti-immigrant framing (Albertson and Gadarian, 2013; Hodson et al., 2013; Hughes and Tuch, 2003; Knoll et al., 2011; Merolla et al., 2013; Terrizzi et al., 2010). That is, women, people with higher educational attainment, and people with liberal rather than conservative political identities tend to express lower levels of outgroup bias (Hodson et al., 2013; Hughes and Tuch, 2003; Terrizzi et al., 2010), which may influence respondent scores on our dependent measures. Partisan affiliation in particular has been shown to shape the impact of anti-immigrant messaging (Albertson and Gadarian, 2013; Knoll et al., 2011; Merolla et al., 2013). To control for gender, we excluded the two participants that reported their gender as nonbinary or thirdgender. We next controlled for political affiliation by transforming our original variable with three categories (i.e., democrat, republican, independent) into two dummy coded variables that reflect identifying as a republican and identifying as an independent.

Finally, we also controlled for participants' race/ethnicity using two variables that captured whether participants identified their racial/ethnic background as Asian (yes/no) or as another minority racial/ethnic identity (yes/no). We included a separate variable for each given the relevance of Asian identities to our study hypotheses and existing data that suggests that non-White Americans express different levels of racial resentment in comparison to White Americans (Milner and Franz, 2019).

3. Results

We first calculated intercorrelations among the dependent variables to assess how the measures of bias toward Asian Americans and xenophobia that were created for this study converged with the two established scales that were also used in this study. Results, shown in Table 1, demonstrate strong bivariate relationships between our measure of COVID-19-specific bias toward Asian Americans and perceptions that Asian Americans pose a realistic threat (r = 0.79) as well as between the measure of the degree to which participants wanted to prioritize resources for non-immigrants and general xenophobia (r = 0.79).

Results from our 2 × 2 × 2 between-subjects ANCOVAs predicting the four measures of outgroup attitudes demonstrate that COVID-19 framing does shape prejudice and xenophobia even when controlling for known predictors of outgroup bias (Fig. 1). Comparing the means between framing conditions, we find effects for the framing of the origin of the virus and the framing of the economic threat of the virus, but not for framing surrounding the physical health threat of the virus (Fig. 2). Below we provide specific results for each framing condition on each of our four dependent measures.

The ANCOVA model predicting COVID-19-specific attitudes toward people of Asian descent demonstrated significant effects for being republican (F (1,1264) = 13.08, p < .001), education (F (1,1264) = 17.60, p < .001), gender (F (1,1264) = 37.96, p < .001), and identifying as Asian (F (1,1264) = 13.51, p < .001). Relevant to our hypotheses, there was also a significant effect of framing condition (F (1, 1264) = 6.26, p = .013). However, there were no significant effects for the described severity of the health threat (F (1,1264) = 0.80, p = .371) or economic threat (F (1,1264) = 0.49, p = .487) of the virus (Table 2). Additionally, none of the interactions were significant. The means for the two framing conditions which discussed the origin of the virus (Table 3) revealed that participants reported more negative attitudes toward Asian Americans in the Chinese framing condition (M = 2.86, SE = 0.04) in comparison to the general framing condition (M = 2.71, SE = 0.04).

The next model predicted beliefs that Asian Americans are a realistic threat to resources in the United States. Of the covariates, being republican (F (1,1264) = 15.53, p < .001), gender (F (1,1264) = 24.53, p < .001), and identifying as Asian (F (1,1264) = 16.24, p < .001) were significantly related to these beliefs. Results also demonstrated a significant effect for the described severity of the economic threat of the virus (F (1,1264) = 5.22, p = .022) but not framing condition (F (1,1264) = 2.55, p = .111) or health threat (F (1,1264) = 1.45, p = .229). There were also no significant interactions. Means for the economic threat conditions revealed that participants in the severe economic threat condition more strongly endorsed beliefs that Asian Americans drain resources (M = 2.70, SE = 0.04) in comparison to participants in the mild economic threat condition (M = 2.58, SE = 0.04).

Results from the ANCOVA predicting beliefs about prioritizing COVID-19-related resources for Americans rather than immigrants showed significant effects for being republican (F (1,1244) = 64.29, p < .001), being independent (F (1,1244) = 8.20, p = .004), gender (F (1,1244) = 13.46, p < .001), identifying as Asian (F (1,1244) = 19.37, p < .001), and identifying as another racial/ethnic minority (F (1,1244) = 4.45, p = .035). There was also a significant effect for framing condition (F (1,1244) = 4.39, p = .036) but nonsignificant effects for health threat (F (1,1244) = 0.19, p = .664) and economic threat (F (1,1244) = 1.05, p = .307). There were also no significant interactions. The means for the two framing conditions which described the origin of the virus demonstrated that people were more likely to endorse that resources should be prioritized for Americans rather than immigrants in the Chinese framing condition (M = 3.10, SE = 0.04) than the general framing condition (M = 2.99, SE = 0.04).

We finally tested an ANCOVA in which framing, health threat, and economic threat predicted general xenophobic attitudes. Results showed a significant effect for being republican (F (1,1244) = 54.14, p < .001), gender (F (1,1244) = 42.29, p < .001), and identifying as Asian (F (1,1244) = 15.87, p < .001). There were also significant effects for framing condition (F (1,1244) = 5.83, p = .016) and economic threat (F (1,1244) = 4.57, p = .033). However, there was no significant effect for health threat (F (1,1244) = 1.06, p = .304) and no significant interactions. The means for the two framing conditions which described the origin of the virus suggest participants in the Chinese framing condition endorsed more xenophobic attitudes (M = 3.01, SE = 0.04) than participants in the general framing condition (M = 2.88, SE = 0.04). Further, means for the economic threat conditions showed participants exposed to information describing a severe economic impact reported higher xenophobia (M = 3.00, SE = 0.04) than participants exposed to information describing a mild economic impact (M = 2.89, SE = 0.04).

4. Discussion

The aim of this study was to empirically assess the effects of public health messages about COVID-19 on expressions of anti-Asian prejudice and xenophobia. Using an experimental design, we assessed the impact of depicting the virus as being imported from China, in addition to depictions that emphasized the physical or economic threat of the virus, on negative attitudes toward Asian Americans and immigrants more generally. Our findings demonstrate that individuals are more likely to express negative beliefs about people of Asian descent, prefer reserving COVID-19 resources for Americans rather than immigrants, and endorse more general xenophobic attitudes when the virus was framed explicitly as originating in China rather than being framed more neutrally. These results lend support for the hypothesis that racial/ethnic prejudice has never truly been on the decline in the U.S. (Bobo, 2017; Bonilla-Silva, 2009) and that certain events, such as the ongoing COVID-19 outbreak, can empower more open expressions of racial and ethnic biases (Crandall et al., 2018; Newman et al., 2020).

This finding also contributes to the ongoing public discourse surrounding the use of terms such as the “Chinese virus” to refer to COVID-19 and provides empirical evidence of the ramifications this type of framing can have for minority populations. Importantly, though, prejudice activated by framing the virus as originating in China extends beyond just the anti-Asian sentiments which have been publicized in mainstream media. This spillover effect may be because anti-immigrant attitudes are less likely to be specific to individual ethnic groups, but reflect xenophobia more generally (Ceobanu and Escandell, 2010). For example, in the U.S. research has found that Hispanics have been the most publicized group of immigrants in recent years, but this framing changes over time and across contexts, despite more general anti-immigrant attitudes remaining present (Valentino et al., 2013). Given that Asian Americans are the racial/ethnic group most likely to be foreign-born in the U.S. (Fussell, 2014), it seems that framing COVID-19 as a threat emerging from China may not only have increased anti-Asian American prejudice but reinforced beliefs that all immigrants pose a threat to Americans. Importantly, these findings suggest that increased prejudice and discrimination create risks not only for Asian Americans, but for other minorities as well, especially immigrants or other individuals perceived as foreign.

Beyond framing of the virus as originating in China, our results suggest that describing the economic impact of COVID-19 as severe rather than mild was also associated with increased xenophobia and beliefs that Asian Americans pose a realistic threat to resources in the U.S. These results suggest that when economic resources are scarce, public health epidemics, such as infectious disease outbreaks, may heighten the expression of prejudice toward specific groups and immigrants generally. These findings also comport with intergroup threat theories (Bailey et al., 2017; Williams and Mohammed, 2013) and theories that implicate resource scarcity as a central cause for intergroup tension (Rodenheffer et al., 2012, Skitka and Tetlock, 1992), and demonstrate that public health crises that threaten economic wellbeing may be a ripe context for prejudice and xenophobia to flourish.

Important to public health campaigns, our findings suggest that negative attitudes toward Asian Americans and immigrants were not impacted by framing conditions that emphasized the potential physical threat of the virus. These results suggest that public health messages that emphasize the health risks of infectious diseases on their own may not trigger the expression of prejudice and xenophobia. This is an encouraging finding given the need to disseminate accurate information about physical health risks associated with disease outbreaks and underscore the seriousness of a potential public health threat.

Instead, public health messaging is most likely to trigger negative attitudes toward Asian Americans and xenophobia when the virus is specifically framed as originating in China and relating to Chinese cultural practices and when messages emphasize the impact an infectious disease will have on the economy. Importantly, emphasizing the connection between COVID-19 and China and the economic threat posed by the pandemic each resulted in increases in at least one of the forms of anti-Asian American prejudice and general xenophobia measured in our study. This demonstrates that bias toward both Asian Americans and immigrants more generally is affected by similar aspects of the unfolding COVID-19 pandemic. The sum of these results suggests that in the context of the COVID-19 pandemic, which both emerged from a foreign country and has strained the U.S. economy, Asian Americans and immigrants are at risk of harm from prejudice and discrimination. Although beyond the scope of this study, it is possible that the COVID-19 pandemic may also be reshaping the racial/ethnic group most closely associated with immigration in the United States.

4.1. Public health implications

Findings from the current paper can inform public health efforts to reduce stigma amid the COVID-19 pandemic. Namely, our results are congruent with the reservations expressed about naming and discussing the virus according to its country of origin (Chiu, 2020; Devakumar et al., 2020; Itkowitz, 2020). Framing an infectious disease as a foreign threat seems to activate prejudice and plausibly explains the growing reports of discrimination toward Asian Americans and immigrants more generally (Liao, 2020; Riek et al., 2006; Sherif and Sherif, 1969; Tondo, 2020; Yang, 2020b). While our data do not allow us to speculate about whether prejudice itself is increasing, the framing of COVID-19 in terms of its country of origin and its impact on the economy does at a minimum appear to be increasing Americans' willingness to express prejudice toward both Asian Americans and immigrants.

In addition to the immediate threats of violence, however, we argue that public health scholars and practitioners should also be concerned about the long-term health impacts of discrimination related to COVID-19. High rates of unemployment and disproportionate economic deprivation, paired with interpersonal discrimination, are likely to have both proximal and distal deleterious effects on mental and physical health for minority populations (Bailey et al., 2017; Chae et al., 2014; Feagin and Bennefield, 2014; Williams and Mohammed, 2013). This suggests a need to take proactive efforts to mitigate the use of such language and framing techniques as a way to reduce the overall public health toll of the virus as well as a need to recognize the unique supports that Asian Americans and immigrants may require or benefit from during this time.

Further, our findings related to the connection between economic threat and prejudice and xenophobia also have implications for public health. While it may be unavoidable to disseminate information about the economic toll of the virus to the public, there may be other strategies that leaders can employ to combat the harmful effects of economic insecurity on prejudice and discrimination. Specifically, it is possible that offering adequate social supports, such as paid sick leave and unemployment, may not only dampen the negative economic effects of the pandemic but also may lessen stigma and prejudice toward vulnerable and immigrant populations perceived to be competing for the same scarce resources. Finally, it is worth underscoring our finding that public health messages which emphasize the severity of an infectious disease may not trigger bias and xenophobia. This is important because, whereas using stigmatizing language is volitional and not required for adequate public health responses, accurately communicating the health risks of COVID-19 is a necessity. Our findings suggest public health officials and others are able to disseminate this information without fear of contributing to stigma.

4.2. Limitations

The primary limitation of this study is that participants were likely exposed to information about COVID-19 prior to completing the study, including messages about the connection between the virus and China and the severity of the economic and health threat of the virus. Recruiting people who had no prior exposure to COVID-19 information and thus no preconceived attitudes was not feasible and we attempted to alleviate this concern by randomly assigning participants to conditions. However, this may have reduced the size of the effects found in the current study. Relatedly, the current study did not find an effect of descriptions of the severity of the health threat of COVID-19 on outgroup attitudes. Given that much of the news coverage surrounding the virus has focused on health consequences, participant perceptions of health threat may have been less susceptible to change via our manipulations.

Another limitation is that we only exposed participants to information about COVID-19 on a single occasion. It is possible that negative attitudes toward Asian Americans and xenophobic attitudes may be further exacerbated by repeated exposure to information that frames the virus in terms of its origin and emphasizes the economic harm of COVID-19. This again suggests the findings in the current study may underestimate the effects of certain types of communication about the virus, particularly when messages are reinforced across time. Finally, though we controlled for the race/ethnicity of participants, we did not control for the nativity status of participants (i.e., whether they were born in the U.S. or were immigrants). Nativity status may have also influenced the extent to which specific framing conditions shaped attitudes toward Asian Americans and xenophobia more generally as participants born outside of the United States may have had more favorable attitudes toward immigrants.

5. Conclusion

Early on in the identification of the novel coronavirus, public health experts carefully weighed the decision of how to name the virus without contributing to stigma. Despite these efforts, the virus has been framed by some leaders and officials in ways that emphasize the country of origin and specific cultural practices that gave rise to the pandemic. Our findings provide empirical evidence that this type of framing in particular is associated with negative beliefs about Asian Americans and immigrants more generally, as are messages that highlight the severe economic impact of the virus. Underscoring the risks posed to physical health did not appear to impact negative outgroup attitudes. In light of these findings, officials should be aware of the potential public health risks of framing the virus as a foreign threat and also take mitigative action to reduce biases that may be activated by the economic repercussions of the virus.
